06381nam a22009735i 9783110709841DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107098417 a10.1515/97831107098412doi  a(DE-B1597)555674  a(OCoLC)1232277655  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0041902bisacsh0485pa880qDE-101  aFT 12800qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/34380:00aElements of Tragedy in Flavian Epic /ced. by Sophia Papaioannou, Agis Marinis. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VII, 210 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Classics - Supplementary Volumes ,x1868-4785 ;v10300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tRepublican Roman Tragedy in Flavian Epic -- tSilius’ Punica and the Traditions of Greek and Roman Tragedy -- tKnowing Me, Knowing You: Epic Anagnorisis and the Recognition of Tragedy -- tApollonius’ ‘Further Voices’: Cameo Appearances of Greek Tragedy in Valerius Flaccus’ Argonautica -- t‘Herculean Tragedy’ in Valerius Flaccus’ Argonautica -- tFinding the Tragic in the Epics of Statius -- tSenecan Heroes and Tyrants in Statius, Thebaid 2 -- tEteocles and Polynices in Statius’ Thebaid: Revisiting Tragic Causality -- tAfterword -- tBibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex Rerum et Nominum -- tIndex Auctorum Antiquorum et Locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the light of recent scholarly work on tragic patterns and allusions in Flavian epic, the publication of a volume exclusively dedicated to the relationship between Flavian epic and tragedy is timely. The volume, concentrating on the poetic works of Silius Italicus, Statius and Valerius Flaccus, consists of eight original contributions, two by the editors themselves and a further six by experts on Flavian epic. The volume is preceded by an introduction by the editors and it concludes with an ‘Afterword’ by Carole E. Newlands.Among key themes analysed are narrative patterns, strategies or type-scenes that appear to derive from tragedy, the Aristotelian notions of hamartia and anagnorisis, human and divine causation, the ‘transfer’ of individual characters from tragedy to epic, as well as instances of tragic language and imagery.The volume at hand showcases an array of methodological approaches to the question of the presence of tragic elements in epic. Hence, it will be of interest to scholars and students in the area of Classics or Literary Studies focusing on such intergeneric and intertextual connections; it will be also of interest to scholars working on Flavian epic or on the ancient reception of Greek and Roman tragedy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aLateinische Epik. 4aRezeption. 4aTragödie. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aFlavian epic.  aLatin epic.  areception.  atragedy.1 aAugoustakis, Antony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, Neil W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCowan, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGervais, Kyle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManuwald, Gesine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarinis, Agis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarinis, Agis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNewlands, Carole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPapaioannou, Sophia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPapaioannou, Sophia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 